    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-01-09T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-01-09T18:00:00-05:00" n="301"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d301">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1115/3980: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Consul General at Hankow</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Josselyn</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-01-09T18:00:00-05:00"
                            >January 9, 1939—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4. Your 2, January 5, 6 p.m. While the Department is not unsympathetic toward the
                    desire of women to return to Hankow and wishes to alter its present policy of
                    advising against their return as soon as conditions warrant such action, it is
                    inclined to concur in the opinion expressed in the final substantive paragraph
                    of your telegram and desires that women, especially those accompanied by
                    children, be discouraged from returning to Hankow. Upon the receipt of advice
                    from you indicating the return of more stable conditions at Hankow, the
                    Department will give the matter further consideration.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Chungking and Shanghai.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Welles</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
